TY  - JOUR
T1  - Aggregation of Utility Functions
AU  - Eisenberg, E.
Y1  - 1961/07/01
PY  - 1961
DA  - 1961/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.7.4.337
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.7.4.337
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 337
EP  - 350
VL  - 7
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We are primarily concerned here with the question of integrability of the total demand in a model in which each consumer acts according to a cardinal utility function and has a fixed monetary income. It is well known that concavity of the various utilities is not sufficient to guarantee integrability, nor even to ensure rationality of the revealed preference. We show that if each personal utility function is homogeneous, in addition to satisfying the usual regularity conditions, then an aggregate utility function can be defined explicitly in terms of the given utilities. Furthermore, under the same assumptions we give a new characterization of equilibrium and show that equilibrium satisfactions are unique.
AB  - We are primarily concerned here with the question of integrability of the total demand in a model in which each consumer acts according to a cardinal utility function and has a fixed monetary income. It is well known that concavity of the various utilities is not sufficient to guarantee integrability, nor even to ensure rationality of the revealed preference. We show that if each personal utility function is homogeneous, in addition to satisfying the usual regularity conditions, then an aggregate utility function can be defined explicitly in terms of the given utilities. Furthermore, under the same assumptions we give a new characterization of equilibrium and show that equilibrium satisfactions are unique.
